title: OpenForge 2.0 Brick Sidewalks and Straight Curbs

description.text:
For instructions on how to get started with OpenForge, take a look at our tutorials.

OpenForge is now a patron supported project. I use the resources that my patrons give me in order to get the resources to let me create more sophisticated tiles with a greater level of detail. Please, support me, and I’ll deliver an ongoing stream of awesome gaming terrain. You can find more about OpenForge and Masterwork Tools at our:

  • Online catalog and backer site
  • Website
  • Forums (Mostly we use facebook now)
  • Twitter
  • Facebook

For each sidewalk/curb tile, print yourself one of brick_sidewalk_textured.* and a base of the same size (2x1, 2x2, 2x4 or 4x4). The streets are in 25mm square basis (which matches Dwarven Forge). If you want that size, print without changes, and print one of the 25mm bases. If you instead want inch squares, scale the street tile on X and Y by 101.6% and print one of the inch bases. Finally, if you want wyloch style tiles (1.25" per square) scale the X and Y by 127%.

Note: All bases for OpenForge City Streets are kept in their own thingiverse entry: OpenForge 2.0 City Street Bases

Other Street Tiles

You can find the rest of this set as it gets released, along with some other city street tiles that people from around thingiverse have been creating in the OpenForge 2 Streets Collection

Quality continues to improve with the printer I'm putting through it's paces. Gearbest provided me with their Tronxy X5s printer. This release had lots of small details, and the prints have come out pretty well. I did still use a lighter to get rid of a light amount of stringing, but compared to earlier prints, the stringing has come way down.

description.text:
This contains all the bases that have been designed that are intended for use with the tiles from the OpenForge 2.0 City Streets set.

For instructions on how to get started with OpenForge, take a look at our tutorials.

OpenForge is now a patron supported project. I use the resources that my patrons give me in order to get the resources to let me create more sophisticated tiles with a greater level of detail. Please, support me, and I’ll deliver an ongoing stream of awesome gaming terrain. You can find more about OpenForge and Masterwork Tools at our:

  • Online catalog and backer site
  • Website
  • Forums (Mostly we use facebook now)
  • Twitter
  • Facebook

There are three factors to consider when selecting a base.

1) The tile size. This will match between the tile and the base, such as 2x2 or 4x2.

2) What size basis do you want the tiles to be in. There are three choices:

  • 25mm - every square is 25mm on a side. This is compatible with Dwarven Forge. There is no need to scale the tile top with 25mm.
  • inch - every square is 1 inch (25.4 mm). This is compatible with Printable Scenery (OpenLOCK), DragonLOCK and HirstArts. Scale the tile top when you print it by 101.6% in the X and Y axes.
  • wyloch - every square is an inch and a quarter (31.75mm). This is compatible with hero's horde and wyloch tiles. Scale the tile top when you print it by 127% in the X and Y axes.

3) What connection system do you want to use. We offer 4 connectivity options:

  • Magnetic - uses 5mm spherical magnets. 1 each along the center of every square that is on the edge of the tile
  • Magnetic + OpenLOCK - uses 5mm spherical magnets. 1 each along the center of every square that is on the edge of the tile. Also has an OpenLOCK connector at the vertice between each square.
  • OpenLOCK - Has an OpenLOCK connector at the vertice between each square.
  • OpenLOCK Triplex - Has an OpenLOCK connector at the vertice between each square, and at the center of each square.

title: Tevo Tarantula stock heatblock sock mold

description.text:
Changelog

2017.10.24 - Created initial version

Description

This is a mold to create a silicone sock for the stock TEVO Tarantula heatblock (20x20x10mm). The mold was created so it could be printed without supports.

Dimensions

Fits the stock nozzle heatblock (20x20x10mm)

Functional description

There are 2 models of heatblocks, you may use the one that fits you better. I have used the one without supports.
You need at least 4x M3 screws and maybe some washers depending on your screw heads.
Use high temperature silicone for this (>300'C)
Use a mold release spray or do like me and mix water with a lot of kitchen soap and put the mold inside, dry it a bit and put the silicone inside. Try to remove any air bubbles before closing the mold.
My mold was sitting for 48h before I opened it, Probably 24h should be more than enough.
Use precision knifes to open it, smooth the surface and cut the excess silicone.

I am taking a printer class and our assignment is to make a paperclip and post it on Thingiverse. This turned into more of a bag clip. After printing the initial test piece, I went back and widened the gap and strengthened the flex arch. The picture is of the test piece.

I would recommend printing at least 50% fill to assure it is strong enough to never break. I would also recommend ABS since it is more flexible.

It is roughly 3.5 inches long x 2 inches wide.

If scaling down, be aware that gap will be smaller and could stick together.

Update:
I put a Rev C out. Strengthening the flex arch made it more brittle and less flexible (Rev A). As a result, I went back and made multiple flex arches to allow flexibility and still add strength. I also lengthened the nose clamp to make it where it opens with less pressure. You could lose a finger the way it was.

Update:
Made a Rev D that keeps the strengthening but makes all flex arches come to a common point so all will be flexed closer to the same amount.

Note:
You may need to hold each side of the nose end and twist open on the end that touches the build plate to help it open the first time. Sometimes the build plate side is connected. Taking a small screw driver and carefully prying it open also works.

I've done a few test cuts with it and...honestly I'm underwhelmed. I'm not sure if the issue is my blades, dxf2gcode's ability to create corner actions for dragknife, my settings in dxf2gcode, or just the nature of drag knifes in general. Even with corner actions I got very sloppy corners, and even the straight cuts weren't super straight because the 8mm bolt isn't a great fit in the bearings.

I'll probably do some more experimenting with gcode improvements and shiming the bolt so it fits tighter...but between my needle cutter, spindle, and laser I don't really need a drag knife like this. Just thought it may be fun as a quieter option than the needle and spindle without the smoke of the laser, but so far I'm not impressed. If you don't need sharp corners in what you're cutting and aren't trying to cut very thick material...it should be fine. But that doesn't cover the stuff I'm most interested in.

description.text:
A couple of people on the forum have mentioned that they've broken blades on their Replicator extruder fans.  Well, that sounds like a need for a fan guard.
I can't decide which one I like better, the radial, or the honeycomb pattern; so I uploaded both.  To tell the truth, I'm not exactly thrilled with either, and I'm expecting someone to come up with a snazzier pattern.
The honeycomb pattern is probably more airflow restrictive, and it might benefit from a larger honeycomb pattern.

The honeycomb version had to be printed slow, with absolute levelosity to get a full grid pattern to print.
The radial pattern is easier.
Either will take a bit of cleanup to sharpen up the drool on the overhang for the clips.
It just slides down over the fans from the top, and it should fit snugly.  Be sure that the bottom is all the way down against the carriage.
UPDATE 7/18/12:  Some people had noted that adding the guard caused a high-pitched whine from the fans.  The new files added (all of the *2 versions) move the guard out a bit from the fan blades.  This should relieve some of the noise.  (I never noticed it much since my Replicator is fully enclosed.)

description.text:
This is a quadcopter design that uses the folded aluminium bars from a fly screen as the arm struts. Note that the motor mounts are designed for a spacing of 42mm diagonally between the motor mounting bolts. This is parametrically adjustable. A bill of materials for my build is available here:
https://docs.google.com/spreadsheet/ccc?key=0Aq6iGQSKjhLXdEZ6RmtVU3BITUVkczgyS0N6aTFQbWc Total weight is 906 grams, with a 2200mAH li-po battery. I have 400 grams of steel strapped to the bottom as a dead weight. It can fly for about five minutes with that load. Explaination video:
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9QZtf85m5vY
Action video:
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VrC8AcyuGwY For more up-to-date, but less-documented parts, I'm hosting the scad files here: https://github.com/tjhowse/quad

Print one hub piece and four each of the other pieces. I suggest you print a few spare legs as they will break upon a rough landing. This is by design, to absorb a bit of the impact. Cut four lengths of flyscreen frame bar. I used 200mm lengths, and this is slightly too small for 9 inch props. I apologise for mixing units there, but propeller dimensions are measured in inches, :(. Fit the motor mounts onto the ends of the rods, making sure to get the polarity right. Make sure you really hammer them on. Measure the length of your arm to make sure it's fully seated into the mount. If you're feeling uncertain about the fit, put a M3x20 screw into the screwhole in the end to lock it in. If you're still feeling unsure, hammer in one of the hub_junction_channel() pieces too. Slip the sleeves over the other ends of the arm, sliding them down the arm about 20mm. They may require some persuasion. Attach the four arms to the hub, then slide the sleeves back inwards towards the hub. Insert the hub_junction_channel pieces into the channel and hammer them inwards to lock it all together. Clip the leg pieces onto the arms, near the end. Done! Your quadcopter frame is complete. Attach motors, electronics and props! Please note that quadcopters are inherently dangerous pieces of equipment. Please be thorough in your testing with props off to get your directions of spin and calibration sorted out. Having your legs cut to ribbons by a rogue quadcopter is nobody's idea of fun.

description.text:
My first upload to thingiverse. I often see people snapping their buffer tube, and it usually leaves little to build upon, so I decided to bite the bullet and finally put a model together. It has a reinforced base to hopefully prevent a second break, and a 6mm hole for a screw to fix it to the receiver. I built this specific one for a LPEG, and the holes for the adjustable stock will probably fit most LPEG stocks. Hope this helps a few people out, and if you remix it to fit higher end stocks (Magpul, PTS etc) upload it to help others out.

If you make one yourself I'd love to see it!

Enjoy!

EDIT- after printing I realised it is a little short- only allowing for 2 length settings on my stock. I also realise there is no space for a connector to lead through the to the stock- I will fix this ASAP. I'm also planning to fix my gun today, and will post pictures of the stock on the weapon later.

title: Everest Gen7 Rear Spare Tire Mount
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a cool cosmetic mod for the Gen7 pro... a rear mount for your spare!

Looks cool and slightly lowers the center of gravity, but the additional rear weight may somewhat negatively impact climbing ability.

This worked well for me printed in PETG at a 0.24mm layer height with 20% infill, 3 shells, no support needed. I recommend PETG for this application as any bumps to the tire may put significant strain on the interlaminar adhesion of the print. ABS would probably work fine, but a strong blow to the side of the tire would break ABS or PLA before it would break PETG.

Recommended but not required is an additional M3x16 machine screw.

Step 1: using a 2mm hex driver, remove the screws from the body hinge.
Step 2: Using a 2.5mm hex driver, remove the spare from the roof rack.
Step 3: Make a mark on the rear of the body 4.5 mm down from the edge of the rear window indentation, and 75mm horizontally from the farthest corner of the window, as seen in the pictures.
Step4: On that mark, use a body reamer or other hole making device to cut a 13.5mm or slightly larger hole.
Step 5: Wedge the printed part in there so that the post sticks out thru the hole you just cut, and use the optional M3 screw to secure the part from the inside.
Step 6: Re-mount the body and install the spare on the rear using the same screw that was holding it on the roof rack.

Enjoy!

Macro Rail para realización automática de Stacker fotograficos en macrofotografía.
La base lleva una tuerca embutida de W 3/4" para colocar en el trípode.
Igualmente en el carro existe un encaje para colocar un tornillo w 3/4" para soportar la cámara.
El motor y la electrónica va tapado mediante una tapa que forma dos departamentos a los lados del motor. Uno para la electrónica de control y otro para el bluetouth.
En este caso no llevamos ventilador, pues el motor no necesita mucha potencia y el driver puede ser alimentado sin refrigeración forzada.
Un final de carrera en el sistema, permite el home del sitema.
He incluido dos versiones de carro, una con dos rodamientos y otra con 4, para usar con según el peso de la cámara. El de 2 rodamientos permite un mayor recorrido, al ser mas corto.
Con un husillo trapezoidal de 2mm por vuelta y un driver de 1/32 el sistema permite una resolución de 0,3 um. Con un driver TMC2100 de 1/16 nos permitirá 0,6 um con total silencio. Más que suficiente para un buen macro.
En las fotos la cámara esta con un objetivo x4 Nikon con profundidad de campo de 20um y con un Tanrom 60 Macro.
Además de la impresión hacen falta un tornillo de avance trapezoidal. http://es.rs-online.com/web/p/products/8625272/?tpr=1
y una tuerca redonda en acero http://es.rs-online.com/web/p/rodamientos-planos-tuercas/8625379/?origin=PSF_428577|acc
o en cobre http://es.rs-online.com/web/p/rodamientos-planos-tuercas/8625345/?origin=PSF_428577|acc

He introducido una mejora, mediante una rueda que porta el tornillo 1/4" para poder amarrar la cámara sin necesidad de tener que girarla sobre la plataforma, ya que en la versión de la fotografía, para enroscar la cámara había que avanzar previamente el Macro Rail.

title: CR-10 flexible filament extruder bracket with adjustable spring tension

description.text:
Intro:
I was exploring the usefulness of oiling the filament when I found that the extruder was slipping on the filament because it was so smooth (after oiling). I realised that in the current design of the extruder, there is no way to tune the tension of the extruder gear on the filament.

After searching the internet, I was surprised that I could not find any other readily available design for our stock extruder to adjust the spring tension, hence I designed this to allow for the spring tension to be adjusted.

Video of how the tension can be adjusted can be found here:
https://youtu.be/szChddRyo70

Note that my design would end up sacrificing one of the mounting holes.

Note:
I recommend printing this in a material with better heat resistance than PLA (I reprinted in PETG) as mine warped from the heat from the extruder motor below it, resulting in a crooked filament path.

Parts list:

  • 1 x M5 30mm bolt (a shorter bolt would make installation difficult)
  • 1 x M5 washer
  • 3 x M5 nut

Assembly:

  • print out the bracket (duh!)
  • insert one of the nuts into the hole. It is friction fitted into the slot. Make sure it goes completely in (see pic). I found it easiest to screw the nut onto a bolt and use the bolt to guide the nut in.
  • screw in the M5 bolt almost all the way and insert the other 2 nuts. There should be a small part of the bolt exposed (2-3mm) to ensure a good hold on the spring when it is installed (see pic).
  • using 2 wrenches, tighten the 2 nuts against each other so that they are locked in place
  • when the bolt is unscrewed all the way, the nut should be more or less flush with the surface (see pic). This would be equivalent to the stock tension.
  • insert the PTFE tube with the appropriate cuts for extruding flexible filament
  • install the bracket onto the z-axis bracket with the extruder arm
  • insert the M5 washer against the stock arm where the spring goes (without this, the spring will turn against the plastic part when you tighten the tension which may strip the plastic, see pic).
  • install the spring and the bowden tube and you are done!! (see pic)

Do note that in terms of dimensional tolerance, I used the CAD file provided by SizZLeR to jump start the design but most of the holes were too small for me (the dimensions by joshvv was perfect for me). Hence in the .stl that is provided, they are sized back up to fit my tolerances. In the included Fusion 360 file, you will find many sketches inside that are used specifically just to enlarge the holes. Use that to adjust whatever hole size that you need to meet your needs.

I would really love to hear your comments on the design and what you think about it, thanks!

Update:
29 Oct 17
I have included a new version for those who are using the extended arm. I found that the screw's position makes it difficult to release the filament. In the extended version, I took the opportunity to also include a cable bracket.

30 Oct 17
I have redrawn the extire extended arm from scratch in order to match the bracket that have designed. The original arm design that I have was a little loose and caused the roller to shift off-axis resulting in the filament getting jammed. The new version 3 of both the stl files are meant to be used as a pair. I have also used the opportunity to design a filament guide into the arm which requires a PTFE tube to be insert to guide the filament in smoothly.

2 Nov 17
Due to some of the minor tolerance issues,I completely redrew from scratch the entire set of bracket and arms and modelled them parametrically so that the alignment of the filament guides would be perfect (at least parametrically). After more than 10 iterations, I believe this is the ultimate in terms of accuracy for the filament guide. Hence I have deleted all previous version and only left behind one version. In this new version, there is also no longer a need for a PTFE tube for the roller portion. You would only need 1 piece (around 5cm long) for the feed from the outside into the rollers.

3 Nov 17
The screw holding the idler gets bent over time if the tension is tuned too high. Hence I designed a version 2 that holds the screw in both the top and bottom position such that it is secured and unlikely to get bent over time. This however requires support to print (and is quite a pain to remove). I included a pic of the new design on how it looks.

description.text:
In my AP Calculus class, my classmates had a difficult time understanding the lesson on volumes of revolution. So at the end of the year, partly as a thank you gift to my teacher and partly as a hope that the year after mine could better understand the lesson, I gave my motivating teacher these models.

Unfortunately and understandably, he retired before the next year. So I decided to submit my models here for all to use, and hopefully benefit from!

Enjoy!

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator 2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.15 to 0.25

Infill:

This does not matter

Notes:

Upon uploading the STL files, I realized that every single part is scaled down 10%. When Slicing your model, the parts all need to be at 1000% scale to compensate. I will try to fix this issue soon, but this is the only issue.

Also, these models were designed with the Makerbot Replicatior 2 in mind, and may not fit all printer types. I hope to be able to resize or remodel soon to fit more small scale printers that probably are in the classrooms.

This model is a visual representation of the lesson in AP Calculus on volumes of revolution. I made these models for my great and well-praised teacher who had the best ambition for all his students. Thank you again Doc! To print the models, the required number of prints are needed: Disc Method 1: 'DM1 Base.stl' is the base of this model
'DM1 L1.stl' is the first of the total 16 layers
'DM1 L2.stl' is the second of the total 16 layers
L3-L16 are the other layers, repectively Disc Method 2: 'DM2 Base.stl' is the base of this model
'DM2 L1.stl' are the middle two layers of the total 16 layers
'DM2 L2.stl' are the next two layers of the 16 total layers
L3-L8 are the other layers Must print two of each layer Washer Method: 'WM Base.stl' is the base of this model
'WM L1.stl' are the middle two layers of the total 16 layers
'WM L2.stl' are the next two layers of the total 16 layers
L3-L8 are the other layers Must print two of each Two Integrals Required: 'TIR Base.stl' is the base of this model
'TIR L1.stl' are the first eight layers of this model
'TIR L2.stl' is the next layer of this model
L3-L9 are the next layers
'TIR L9.stl' is the last layer of the model Must print eight of the first layer

The lesson is on volumes of revolution in AP Calculus; the models should act as a visual aid during lesson. I have specifically designed the words to be read by everyone in the classroom independent of seating. This is the lesson that I based these models from, and is in the pictures above as well.

The only extra materials needed to create these models are 1/8 in rods acting as vertical supports.  These rods will be cut to the appropriate length (6 x 6" and 1 x 5.5").  I would also recommend lightly smoothing out the cut edges for better alignment of each layer. Three of the 6" rods will be used in "Disc Method 1", three more for "Two Integrals Required", and finally the 5.5" rod is used in "Disc Method 2".
Happy Printing!

description.text:
ThingPro - The 3D Printed 3-Way Selfie Stick

This is selfie stick that I designed for use with my GoPro Hero 6 Black but it can potentially be used for any camera or phone with the proper mount.

It is essentially the same as the GoPro 3-Way with some modifications to allow for 3D printing.

I am going to try and keep improving this design over time, so I appreciate any feedback or comments that the community has.

My next improvement is to encapsulate a tri-pod within the handle of the stick as the GoPro 3-way does.

Enjoy!

Hero 4 not included. :)

Notes:

I sliced this with Simplify3D with supports in all of the holes and under some of the small overhangs.

I printed this in PLA without rafts using painters tape and a glue stick in order to prevent warping which can be a challenge due the geometry of extension 1 & 2.

This design is meant to use a couple off the shelf items in conjunction with the 3D printed parts.

  1. M5x1.5 Heat Insert (QTY. 3):
    The ones that I used are from McMaster Carr and can be found here: https://www.mcmaster.com/#94180a361/=19z0v2k

The stick is designed to accept inserts with these dimensions so be careful.

Use a soldering gun to melt these into each arm.

  1. M5x1.5x30mm Threaded Rod (QTY. 2):
    Again, the ones I used are from McMaster Carr and can be found here: https://www.mcmaster.com/#90435a104/=19z0wgm

A word of caution - I cut the equivalent threads into the Knob to accept these rods but they are a bit tight and require some finesse to install. The threaded rod should stick out approx. 16.5mm from the end of the knob. I used Loctite 425 to ensure the rods stay in the Knobs!

Discussion focuses on his chair paintings: Vincent's Chair with His Pipe and Gaugain's Arm Chair. http://www.vggallery.com/painting/p_0498_0499.htm Students will observe that the two chair paintings look and feel completely different. They will discuss what the paintings tell you about their owner. Students will then make a chair out of clay that represents themselves and their personality. A 3D printed chair frame will be used as the skeleton for their custom chair. Completed chairs will be painted and shared with their classmates for comparison. This is an art project the art teacher used to do entirely with clay. But she found it was difficult for the 3rd grade to make a chair out of clay from scratch so she wanted a 3D printed plain chair frame that could be used as the base for the student's sculpture.

title: Speaker Enclosure Dayton RS100
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a ported speaker enclosure for the 4" full-range Dayton Audio RS100. The driver is actually more like 3", but Dayton uses the outer edge of the frame for this measurement. The volume is approx. 0.1 ft3 for a spec'd F3 rolloff of 67Hz(!). Remember, it IS a ~3" driver - it's not going to shake the walls, but there's some usable range down there. While an enclosure made of PLA is never going to be as acoustically dead as e.g. MDF, I added a Dynamat-like material to the interior to help. These sound surprisingly good - the high end and imaging is better than the Tectonic Elements used in my other projects, near and on-axis. The Tech Elements win off-axis, in my opinion.
I continue to be impressed with the performance of many of these small full-range drivers.

See my remix for the Tectonic Elements TEBM65C20F-8 3-1/2" BMR.

Filament: Makergeeks Maker Series Nuclear Green (from the subscription box, I think). I ran out, hence the darker green for the back bit.

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Mk2

Resolution:

0.3

Infill:

I use 30-50%

Notes:

The design is meant to minimize needed supports while under the constraint of printing face down. The back is meant to be bridged, using no supports. Supports are required in two places:

  1. The inset ring that the speaker mounts to.
  2. The front of the port on the inside of the enclosure.

This is one instance where I skip no upper support layers, since I want the mounting face to be as flat/solid as possible, and I can mar up that (hidden) surface removing the supports.

The corners of the front face are susceptible to lifting if bed adhesion is not solid. I usually have some significant bubbling of the PEI around the perimeter with this print, and I'm 50/50 on slightly lifted corners.

You may wish to print only the first several mm of the front and do a test fit, as the frame diameter will have some manufacturing tolerance, not to mention differences in printer calibrations. You might also check the bolt fit.

Lately, I tend to increase line width to 0.7 in order to reduce print time, and minimize use of infill. I use 4 perimeters and 4 top & bottom layers, either way.

I lined the interior with Noico sound deadening mat, made for automotive applications, and moderately filled the enclosure with wool fiber.

Given the need for bridging on the back surface, I decided to close it entirely, and simply drill or cut out the necessary hole(s) for binding posts.

For mounting the driver, I use M3 button heads ~10mm long.
